review_blob: Smooth as silk. Stout bitterness leavened/expanded by coffee and lactose flavourings. On tap at the Wheaty.
beer_name: 8 Wired Flat White Coffee Milk Stout

review_blob: Decent porter, nice choccy malt finish. No hops to speak of, but I dont miss them. On hand-pump at the Wheaty.
Collaboration with Yeastie Boys. Great taste for a mid-strength. Big on the hops, and not a lot of bottom end, but a nice drinker. On tap at the Wheaty.
Taking into account its relatively low ABV, this is very tasty ale, with complex malt flavours and a chocolate and coffee finish. A great session ale. On tap at the Wheaty.
As youd expect for a strong APA - strong, slightly burnt, malt flavour, well-balanced with hops. Wouldnt say it was special. On tap at the Wheaty.
Yes, its peaty... hello?! Easier with a blocked nose, like mine, but still... Perfectly drinkable, and I like the unique, smoky after-taste, so there.
Probably Jades "signature beer" - max hops, so plenty of bitterness. Not enough "bottom end", for mine, but distinctive, anyway. On tap at the Wheaty (of course).
About as interesting and flavoursome as youd expect an 8%+ DIPA to be. Nice complexity, given its practically all hop flavours.
Rated as a mid-strength. Fantastically full-flavoured. Way ahead of any other mid-strength, or even sessionable, Ive had. On tap at the Wheaty.
Alright, but the taste is not quite there, for mine, even considering the low ABV. On tap at the Wheaty.
Smooth! Slightly fruity palate beautifully offset by the hoppy finish. On tap at the Wheaty.
beer_name: Two Birds / Cavalier The Cavalier Bird Belgian IPA

review_blob: Golden ale style, with botritised viognier - added with the hops, if I remember rightly - not convinced by it, but a neutral rating cos its not my style of beer, anyway. On tap(? - tasting session) at the Wheaty.
beer_name: Yeastie Boys The Sun Before the Darkness

review_blob: Light, Belgian White style, with botritised viognier - added with the hops, if I remember rightly - not convinced by it, but a neutral rating cos its not my style of beer, anyway. On tap(? - tasting session) at the Wheaty.
Made with Russian Caravan tea, which I think suits the style of beer ok - I liked it. On tap at the Wheaty.
A bit too hoppy for mine, but a nice-drinking amber nevertheless. On tap at the Wheaty.
Well, its fine. Not a world-beater. Would probably expect a bit more complexity for the abv. Bottled at the brewery.
Just an ordinary-tasting black ale - not a Porter. Nothing wrong with it. Bottled at the brewery.
Quite a distinctive smoky flavour, especially in the aftertaste. Otherwise a fairly standard brown ale, not overly complex and not nutty enough for mine. Bottled at the brewery.
For mine, the alcohol flavour over-takes the stout flavours too much. It does leave a pleasing taste on the teeth and lips, that I cant describe, but not a big-flavoured stout. On tap at the Wheaty.
beer_name: Birra del Borgo Imperiale Imperial Russian Stout

review_blob: Perfectly ok, just not a stand-out. Youd expect a bit more flavour given the alcohol content. Coopers stout could compete with it. On tap at the Wheaty.
Cant fault it. Complex, smoky flavour, bitter enough, good balance, nice aftertaste. On tap at the Wheaty.

Jeez - chocolate, red wine, whisky... an array of flavours, especially on the way down. (Later in the glass) Ok, the law of diminishing returns kicks in. In the end, its a wonderful journey, but one is probably enough.
Yeah, its pretty hoppy, fairly distinctive, now Im starting to distinguish different hop flavours. Almost a Pilsner, if you shut your eyes. Needs a bit of bottom end, for mine. On tap at the Wheaty.
Dont expect your classic brown ale taste from this. The tea gives it quite a sour taste. On tap at the Wheaty.
Confusing, but not a bad drop. The nose convinces you youre about to drop into a double IPA, whilst the colour is saying malt, malt. Well, a bit of both dont hurt. On tap at the Wheaty.
Intriguing. The nose doesnt give anything away, but the taste is full of surprises - toffee and bubblegum notes in quite a satisfying finish. On tap at the Wheaty.
Interesting nose of chocolate and citrus. Taste is a bit on the sour side, for mine. Nicely complex, though. On tap at the Wheaty.
Just a nice, smooth, vanilla-y stout. Nothing special. From the hand-pump at the Wheaty.
Cracking beer. Works all the taste buds. Plenty of bitterness, a bit of fruit, healthy bottom end and a good, hoppy finish. On tap at the Wheaty.
A bit too chocolate-y for my taste - I like my browns nutty. Not very complex, really, even considering the lower alcohol content. On tap at the Wheaty.

Nice and full-flavoured for a sessionable ale. Almost an IPA in nose and initial palate.
From the tap at the brewery.
Just a massive dose of hops with extra hops, and no flavour to go with it. Good, if you like that sort of thing, but I like a bit of complexity to go with my hoppiness.
Nice lot of complexity. A good, nutty brown ale. From the hand-pump at the Wheaty. xxx

Definitely grows on you. Massively hopped, so all bitterness at first, but the malt gradually works its way through, to the point that youre looking forward to the next one. From the tap at the Wheaty.
Just a more malty IPA, really. Little complexity. A reasonable drink, nothing special. From the tap at the Wheaty.
A very nice, complex American pale ale. Lovely honey-ish after-taste. From the tap at the Wheaty.
Pretty ordinary IPA, for mine. Lots of hops, not sufficiently balanced by the malt. Little complexity.
A beautifully complex IPA. I got seaweed flavours, over the expected hoppy goodness. Tastes different on the way in to what it does on the way down! Drank it on tap at the Wheatsheaf Hotel, Adelaide.
